For this DIY exercise, we have an R Markdown document with missing code. Our analysis is of th "Sydney beaches dataset, which contains info about the weather on a variety of Sydney beaches at different times.

library(tidyverse)
library(here)
data_file <- here("data", "sydneybeaches3.csv")
beaches <- read_csv(file = data_file)

The plot below is a scatterplot showning temperature on the x-axis and rainfall on the y-axis. First, run this section of code and see what happens:

ggplot(
  beaches, 
  aes(x=temperature, 
      y=rainfall)) + 
geom_point()

Now construct a new plot that makes the points larger and colours them according to season. (Question: why does it do something different for the season and season_name variables?)

ggplot(
  beaches, 
  aes(x=temperature, 
      y=rainfall,
      colour = season_name)) + 
geom_point(size = 3)

#categorical versus continuous

Next we need to add a title. Create a new plot that uses the labs() function to add an informative title to the plot

ggplot(
  beaches, 
  aes(x=temperature, 
      y=rainfall,
      colour = season_name)) + 
geom_point(size = 3)+
labs(
  title = "Rainfall by Temperature",
  subtitle = "Varying by season",
  x = "Temperature (degrees celsius)",
  y = "Rainfall (mm)"
)

Finally, add the bw theme and facet by season as well.

ggplot(
  beaches, 
  aes(x=temperature, 
      y=rainfall,
      colour = season_name)) + 
geom_point(size = 3)+
  facet_wrap(~season_name)+
  theme_bw() +
labs(
  title = "Rainfall by Temperature",
  subtitle = "Varying by season",
  x = "Temperature (degrees celsius)",
  y = "Rainfall (mm)"
)
